If such a set $A$ existed, Condition 1 implies that for a sequence of $n_k \to \infty$, $A \cap (0, n_k) \subseteq \{ p < n_k \mid n_k - p \in \mathbb{P} \}$. The size of this set of shifted primes is bounded by the number of Goldbach representations of $n_k$.
Standard sieve bounds (related to the Hardy-Littlewood tuple conjecture) show that for any large $n$, the number of such primes is $O(n / (\log n)^2)$.
However, Condition 2 requires $|A \cap (0, n)| \gg n / \log n$.
Since $n / (\log n)^2 \ll n / \log n$ for large $n$, this is a contradiction. Thus, such a set does not exist. The statement is False.

